00:17:31.860 --> 00:17:38.640
that's emanating from that point. In other words,&nbsp;
the tree that has that as a root, okay. So that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:38.640 --> 00:17:44.880
that one along with two edges and these two, two&nbsp;
down here. So that's like a little sub-tree, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:44.880 --> 00:17:49.800
in fact, there it is. There, and you can sort of&nbsp;
see that's what's called b. So what we can do is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:49.800 --> 00:17:56.400
in this diagram here we can replace this sub-tree&nbsp;
with just a single node which is the root of it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:56.400 --> 00:18:04.680
and we put a little, say, box around it, okay,&nbsp;
and letter b, telling us that what we've done is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:04.680 --> 00:18:11.400
we've made a substitution or we've sort of rubbed&nbsp;
some stuff out, and this is then a placeholder for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:17.100
some additional stuff which is perhaps off the&nbsp;
page or is recorded in memory somewhere else,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:17.880 --> 00:18:22.740
okay. So in this case here, we see there's a&nbsp;
little square around it, meaning there's actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:22.740 --> 00:18:28.860
more stuff, there's another tree coming from that&nbsp;
node, but we have to find it somewhere else. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:28.860 --> 00:18:34.260
so we look over here, okay, here's b, so then&nbsp;
we could recover this by putting that back in.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:34.920 --> 00:18:40.500
Similarly, this one here, that node there&nbsp;
is replaced with a little square around it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:46.800
and we forget about the stuff below, and the&nbsp;
letter c, you know, so this is representing this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:46.800 --> 00:18:55.140
sort of sub-tree, node, node, and a leaf there.&nbsp;
So this is a more efficient way of representing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:55.140 --> 00:19:00.180
this thing that sort of compresses some of the&nbsp;
information perhaps that we don't really need.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:00.900 --> 00:19:06.120
Now there's a corresponding way of thinking about&nbsp;
that over here, in the sense of what we're doing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:06.120 --> 00:19:12.240
is we're sort of closing the boxes, okay, but&nbsp;
recording the contents of the box somewhere else.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:12.240 --> 00:19:18.600
So corresponding to what I did over here, this&nbsp;
b one over here is this one here. So going from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:18.600 --> 00:19:23.760
this diagram to this diagram, what I've done is&nbsp;
I've sort of shaded the box so you no longer can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:29.040
see inside. There's something inside, perhaps it&nbsp;
doesn't have to be, but there could be something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:35.340
inside, but we don't know what it is. But over&nbsp;
here in different locations, we see that actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:35.340 --> 00:19:41.400
this box is actually this one here. And similarly&nbsp;
this box c which has also been shaded so we lose&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:41.400 --> 00:19:46.320
the information, but it's over here somewhere,&nbsp;
okay. So this is a way that if we're doing certain&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:46.320 --> 00:19:53.880
manipulations and we don't actually need to know&nbsp;
what the sort of finer structure is inside these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:53.880 --> 00:19:59.640
boxes inside other boxes, okay, we might be&nbsp;
making a calculation that only requires us to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:06.300
look at things down to a certain depth, and what's&nbsp;
below that is sort of irrelevant for the actual&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:06.300 --> 00:20:13.920
computation we're interested in. So this kind of&nbsp;
representation or simplification, I think, can be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:18.780
helpful in that kind of context. You see there's&nbsp;
a natural parallel between what we're doing here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:18.780 --> 00:20:23.520
in the tree world and what we're doing here in&nbsp;
the more familiar sort of m-set or box world.

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:29.340
Okay, so now let's get to the arithmetic with&nbsp;
trees, and I'm just going to give you this&nbsp;&nbsp;

