is admittedly of an elementary nature, but still&nbsp;
the unfamiliarity of it probably does require some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:37.620 --> 00:21:43.320
practice. So actually in that direction while I'm&nbsp;
talking about that, maybe I could ask some of my&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:43.320 --> 00:21:49.440
viewers to think about, if you're interested in&nbsp;
this topic, of creating some resources that will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:56.160
help us to sort of gain some experience in this&nbsp;
world. So I think it would be nice to have some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:56.700 --> 00:22:03.900
problem sets like little homework exercises that&nbsp;
we could do, maybe with solutions which have been&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:03.900 --> 00:22:11.460
carefully worked out so that we can see whether&nbsp;
our intuition is a good one. Okay, so here's an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:11.460 --> 00:22:20.640
example of such a thing. So here are two m-sets,&nbsp;
a and b, represented in tree form. Okay, so here's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:26.700
the root, we have three children, one of them is a&nbsp;
leaf, the other two have some branches, that's of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:26.700 --> 00:22:33.660
depth two, and that's one that's depth three. So&nbsp;
in terms of our familiar sort of algebra notation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:33.660 --> 00:22:41.340
this corresponds to an algebraic expression in our&nbsp;
variables, well, in numbers and variables. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:41.340 --> 00:22:48.480
in this case, 1 plus alpha 0 plus alpha 1. The&nbsp;
one corresponds to that leaf down there, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:48.480 --> 00:22:53.340
so that's just a single zero inside the big&nbsp;
m-set, that corresponds to the number one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:53.340 --> 00:23:02.160
This thing here, it's like an m-set inside the&nbsp;
big m-set, there's an m-set which has a single&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:10.140
zero in it, so that's like this. This combination&nbsp;
here is one, but it's inside the bigger m-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:10.140 --> 00:23:15.900
so it has the interpretation of alpha zero. And&nbsp;
when we go one more, so when we have an m-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:15.900 --> 00:23:22.560
inside an m-set with a zero in it, then that's&nbsp;
alpha one. Over here, b, we have another one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:22.560 --> 00:23:27.420
so there's the root and there's a leaf coming&nbsp;
down there, and here's a node which has two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:27.420 --> 00:23:34.320
leaves coming out here. So this thing here by&nbsp;
itself is the number two, but when the number two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:34.320 --> 00:23:40.440
is appearing as, you know, down from the root,&nbsp;
it has to be interpreted in a different way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:40.440 --> 00:23:46.440
okay. That's like the number two in an m-set,&nbsp;
that's different from the number two. So that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:46.440 --> 00:23:53.400
has the interpretation of being alpha zero squared&nbsp;
in terms of this fundamental variable, the zeroth&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:53.400 --> 00:23:58.560
variable, alpha zero. So this is 1 plus alpha&nbsp;
zero squared, that's an interpretation of that.

00:23:58.560 --> 00:24:05.040
Okay, so here are the various operations that we&nbsp;
know so far how to do, and so the simplest one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:05.040 --> 00:24:11.160
is of course addition, where we just take these&nbsp;
things and add them. And what we're doing there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:11.160 --> 00:24:19.680
one way of thinking about it is we're just, we're&nbsp;
just sort of chopping these things off here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:19.680 --> 00:24:27.240
and then taking these, the constituent&nbsp;
entries, which are themselves little trees,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:27.240 --> 00:24:34.740
okay, and we're just putting them all together.&nbsp;
So this tree right here gets copied, that's a new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:35.580 --> 00:24:43.680
element of this, this new m-set, okay, this one&nbsp;
here gets copied, and this one here gets copied.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:43.680 --> 00:24:52.140
Similarly, this one gets copied and this one here&nbsp;
gets copied. Okay, so you could think about it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:52.140 --> 00:24:57.300
perhaps as a sort of way we're sort of snipping or&nbsp;
cutting those edges there, and cutting those edges&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:57.300 --> 00:25:04.140
there, and taking those five edges and putting&nbsp;
them together within a new node. That's the tree&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:04.140 --> 00:25:11.640
version of taking the contents of these two m-sets&nbsp;
and dumping them out into into another box, okay.

00:25:11.640 --> 00:25:21.360
A times B, this is a times B, and how do we&nbsp;
get that? Well, what we have to do is we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:21.360 --> 00:25:27.720
to look at the elements of a. So there are three&nbsp;
elements of a, each of them is themselves a tree,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:27.720 --> 00:25:32.880
and there are two elements of b, each of them is&nbsp;
itself a tree, and we have to take all possible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:32.880 --> 00:25:40.500
combinations of elements of a and elements of b,&nbsp;
like pairs, maybe that tree and that tree, and we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:40.500 --> 00:25:47.820
have to add them, they're m-sets so they can be&nbsp;
added. So for example, when we do that, we take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:47.820 --> 00:25:52.620
this thing here which is really like the m-set&nbsp;
which is what we're calling one, and this is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:52.620 --> 00:25:58.200
m-set zero, and we add one and zero, we get one,&nbsp;
okay. So the effect of adding this and this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:58.200 --> 00:26:04.080
just to get this, so that's why that's appearing&nbsp;
over there. And similarly, this plus this tree is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:04.080 --> 00:26:10.440
it's this one here, and this one plus this is also&nbsp;
this one here, okay. So now the next three are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:10.440 --> 00:26:16.800
obtained by taking these three and adding this one&nbsp;
to it, okay. So for example, if we take this tree&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:16.800 --> 00:26:23.400
here, and we take this tree here, and we add them.&nbsp;
So this is a tree with one leaf, this is a tree&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:23.400 --> 00:26:29.940
with two leaves, we add them, we get a tree with&nbsp;
three leaves. When we add this one and this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:29.940 --> 00:26:39.660
we get a tree that has a root there, and then it&nbsp;
has this sub-tree coming down, and also two leaves&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:39.660 --> 00:26:45.060
coming out. And finally, when we add this to this,&nbsp;
well this is zero again, so we're just getting our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:47.460 --> 00:26:52.800
thing that we started with there. So this&nbsp;
is a times b, and what is it algebraically?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:53.520 --> 00:27:03.720
Well, sort of read through things, this one here&nbsp;
is one, okay, and this one here is a one but it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:03.720 --> 00:27:10.260
contained in a big bracket so that's alpha&nbsp;
zero. This is alpha one. This one here is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:11.640 --> 00:27:16.740
okay, this one here is maybe the next simplest&nbsp;
one. This one here is alpha zero squared,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:16.740 --> 00:27:22.200
okay. This one here is alpha zero cubed,&nbsp;
and this one here is a combination of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:25.980
alpha zeros. There's two, sort of two&nbsp;
of them, so alpha zero squared there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:25.980 --> 00:27:33.960
but there's also an alpha one, so it corresponds&nbsp;
to this polynomial in alpha zero and alpha one.

00:27:36.360 --> 00:27:44.520
And what about a caret b? Okay, so we're going&nbsp;
to change our notation just a little bit. I was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:44.520 --> 00:27:49.500
talking about exponentiation, maybe that's not&nbsp;
really such a great terminology. A number of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:56.400
viewers have suggested that, and I think that's&nbsp;
reasonable, but I sort of like this symbol,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:56.400 --> 00:28:02.220
so I'm going to stick with a suggestion that&nbsp;
a viewer made, that we stick with this thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:02.220 --> 00:28:09.900
here and call it the caret, c-a-r-e-t, okay.&nbsp;
So a caret b, what is that? So by definition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:09.900 --> 00:28:14.940
what we have to do is we have to take these things&nbsp;
here and take the various sub-trees, the elements&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:14.940 --> 00:28:21.660
of this one, the elements of this one, and we have&nbsp;
to pairwise multiply them, multiply them, not add.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:21.660 --> 00:28:25.500
Over here we were adding them, here we have to&nbsp;
multiply them. So for example, we have to take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:25.500 --> 00:28:31.920
this sub-tree and multiply it by this sub-tree,&nbsp;
okay. But this sub-tree is zero, when we multiply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:31.920 --> 00:28:37.560
something by zero, we get zero. So we get a zero,&nbsp;
zero, zero. The first three are going to be zeros,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:38.400 --> 00:28:44.700
in fact we're going to get another zero because,&nbsp;
because when we multiply this one by this one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:44.700 --> 00:28:50.520
here, we also get a zero. So the two that are&nbsp;
non-trivial are the product of this and this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:50.520 --> 00:28:56.940
which is this and this and this. So let's just&nbsp;
check that. So the product of this tree and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:56.940 --> 00:29:05.460
this tree, how do you take the product? Well,&nbsp;
you have to look at all possible pairs of sub,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:06.180 --> 00:29:11.220
or elements. This one has one element, this one&nbsp;
has two elements, so we have to take a pair like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:11.220 --> 00:29:15.720
this and we have to add them, all right. So zero&nbsp;
plus zero is zero, zero plus zero, zero. So we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:15.720 --> 00:29:22.140
getting two possible zeros, and when we do the&nbsp;
same thing over here, we have to take this tree,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:22.140 --> 00:29:30.780
okay, starting from there, and this tree, and we&nbsp;
have to multiply them. So how do we do that? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:30.780 --> 00:29:35.340
we have to take the elements of this one, there's&nbsp;
only one element, namely the tree starting there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:35.340 --> 00:29:41.820
and there's two elements of this one, and we&nbsp;
have to add those, okay. So when we add this one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:41.820 --> 00:29:47.580
with this one, well, we just get this thing, and&nbsp;
when we add it with this one, we get this thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:47.580 --> 00:29:52.620
because zero plus anything is the anything,&nbsp;
all right. So that's what we end up getting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:52.620 --> 00:29:59.760
by taking this combination with this combination,&nbsp;
multiplying, multiplying this tree with this tree.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:01.260 --> 00:30:06.960
And what does this look like&nbsp;
algebraically? Well, this is a four,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:07.740 --> 00:30:17.640
this is alpha zero squared, same thing like that.&nbsp;
And this thing here is, well, uh, this was like an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:17.640 --> 00:30:25.080
alpha, alpha one, and we have two of them coming&nbsp;
out here, so that's like alpha one squared. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:25.080 --> 00:30:30.420
that's the way the caret operation works on these&nbsp;
things, which is, you know, a little bit strange&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:30.420 --> 00:30:38.880
to us. Admittedly, this is a kind of a strange new&nbsp;
arithmetic. We're in a kind of unusual world here.

00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:42.300
So the natural question though&nbsp;
is, is this a consistent world,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:42.300 --> 00:30:47.340
and is it an interesting world? Well, if we just&nbsp;
restrict ourselves to addition and multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:47.340 --> 00:30:52.560
it's certainly useful because we're&nbsp;
recovering polynomial algebra in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:52.560 --> 00:30:57.720
actually an unbounded number of variables.&nbsp;
That's already a very rich discipline,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:58.380 --> 00:31:03.840
and in fact in our next video, we're going&nbsp;
